{"questionId":"12278","questionHtml":"<p>The square matrix <strong><em>X</em></strong> is such that <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>3</sup>&nbsp;= 0. Show that the inverse of the matrix (<strong><em>I</em> </strong>–<strong> <em>X</em></strong>) is <strong><em>I</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>For multiplying (<strong><em>I</em></strong> – <strong><em>X</em></strong>)(<strong><em>I</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>= <strong><em>I</em></strong><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;+ <strong><em>IX</em></strong> + <strong><em>IX</em></strong><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;– <strong><em>XI </em></strong>– <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;– <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>3</sup>&nbsp;= <strong><em>I</em> </strong>+ <strong><em>X</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;– <strong><em>X</em></strong> – <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;– <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>3</sup>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)(A1) </strong></em></p>\n<p>= <strong><em>I</em></strong> – <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>3</sup>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1 </strong></em></p>\n<p>= <strong><em>I</em></strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1 </strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><em>AB</em></strong> = <strong><em>I</em></strong>&nbsp;⇒ <strong><em>A</em></strong><sup>–1</sup>&nbsp;= <strong><em>B</em></strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (R1) </strong></em></p>\n<p>(<strong><em>I</em></strong> – <strong><em>X</em></strong>)(<strong><em>I</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong> + <strong><em>X</em></strong><sup>2</sup>) = <strong><em>I</em></strong> ⇒ (<strong><em>I</em></strong> – <strong><em>X</em></strong>)<sup>–1</sup>&nbsp